        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "## Cumulative Stability Constants (log β) from SRD-46\n\nThe database reports **cumulative** log β values (i.e., log βₙ for the ML_n complex). The highest stoichiometry measured for each metal is shown below:\n\n| Rank | Metal | Complex | log β (SRD-46) | Temp (°C) | Ionic Str. | Softness Class |\n|------|-------|---------|---------------|-----------|------------|----------------|\n| 🥇 1 | **Hg²⁺** | HgL₄ | **21.8** | 25 | 0.0 M | Soft (Class b) |\n| 🥈 2 | **Cd²⁺** | CdL₄ | **3.6** | 25 | 0.0 M | Borderline soft |\n| 🥉 3 | **Pb²⁺** | PbL₂ | **1.0** | 25 | 0.0 M | Borderline hard |\n\n> **Note on stoichiometry:** The SRD-46 data show that Hg²⁺ and Cd²⁺ form tetrakis complexes ML₄ (log β₄), while Pb²⁺ only reaches ML₂ (log β₂). The log β values are cumulative, so they reflect the overall stability of the highest complex formed, not a simple stepwise K₁. Nonetheless, the trend is unambiguous across all stoichiometries.",
